And he would have delighted at the Party at the Palace as he had watched the Coronation in 1953 up inside the soaring arches of Westminster Abbey. Bond, who died in 2017 aged 91, was a BBC crew member when he got a bird's eye view of the ceremony. Daughter Karen Jankel, 63, said: "He got a glimpse of it all. He respected the Royal Family." Karen also revealed she had trouble keeping secret how Paddington would take tea with Her Majesty for the TV sketch that kickstarted the Party at the Palace. She said: "I was let into the secret but had to sit on it. Just before, I told family they must watch. It was a very hard secret to keep. It was brilliant... the biggest honour." 